domain_key|pattern_key|score_shape|rank_1_signal_key|rank_2_signal_key|rank_3_signal_key|rank_4_signal_key|mechanics_title|core_mechanism|why_it_shows_up|what_it_protects|status|lookup_key
leadership-approach|people_results_process_vision|concentrated|people|results|process|vision|How People organises the response|People is likely to organise the first response by checking trust, communication, inclusion, and what people need in order to move with the work. Results and Process add useful checks, while Vision may need deliberate attention before the response becomes too narrow.|This shows up when pressure makes trust, shared understanding, and commitment feel like the clearest way to begin. The next signals test whether the work also has a clear outcome and a decision people can act on, usable structure and a sequence people can trust, and a wider direction and a reason for the choice being made.|It protects the work from low trust, weak buy-in, poor communication, and people being left behind by the pace of work. The main range to add is a stronger future frame, meaning, and possibility, especially when the first response has already created movement.|active|leadership-approach::people_results_process_vision::concentrated
leadership-approach|people_results_process_vision|paired|people|results|process|vision|How People and Results work together|People and Results tend to operate as a close working pair. People gives the first entry point, while Results quickly changes how the response is explained, organised, or carried into action.|This shows up when the situation seems to need both communication, confidence, and shared commitment and a clear outcome and a decision people can act on. Process can steady the pair, and Vision is the range to bring in before the pair becomes too narrow.|It protects the link between trust and shared commitment and outcome and follow-through. It also needs enough room for a stronger future frame, meaning, and possibility when the top pair starts to take most of the attention.|active|leadership-approach::people_results_process_vision::paired
leadership-approach|people_results_process_vision|graduated|people|results|process|vision|How the pattern moves from People to Vision|The pattern tends to move in steps: People starts the response, Results gives the next influence, Process adds support, and Vision may need to be brought in deliberately.|This shows up when leadership attention follows a clear order rather than moving evenly between several options. Each step adds a different check on what the work now needs.|It protects a coherent sequence from trust and shared commitment towards structure and standards. The main watch point is leaving a stronger future frame, meaning, and possibility until the work has already narrowed.|active|leadership-approach::people_results_process_vision::graduated
leadership-approach|people_results_process_vision|balanced|people|results|process|vision|How the pattern moves between People, Results, Process, and Vision|The pattern may have several usable entry points. People may appear first, but context can quickly call for Results, Process, or Vision without making the response inconsistent.|This shows up when the situation contains several kinds of leadership demand at once. The useful skill is naming which need is current rather than moving between them silently.|It protects flexibility across trust and shared commitment, outcome and follow-through, structure and standards, and direction and future consequence. It needs a clear current priority so others can follow the shift.|active|leadership-approach::people_results_process_vision::balanced
leadership-approach|people_results_vision_process|concentrated|people|results|vision|process|How People organises the response|People is likely to organise the first response by checking trust, communication, inclusion, and what people need in order to move with the work. Results and Vision add useful checks, while Process may need deliberate attention before the response becomes too narrow.|This shows up when pressure makes trust, shared understanding, and commitment feel like the clearest way to begin. The next signals test whether the work also has a clear outcome and a decision people can act on, a wider direction and a reason for the choice being made, and usable structure and a sequence people can trust.|It protects the work from low trust, weak buy-in, poor communication, and people being left behind by the pace of work. The main range to add is clearer steps, standards, and handover, especially when the first response has already created movement.|active|leadership-approach::people_results_vision_process::concentrated
